#X msg 829 224 \$1 2000 0 \, bang;
#X obj 829 252 envgen~ -curve 1;
#X text 536 460 Note that [envgen~] \, with all its several features and curve settings \, also includes the same curve factor used in [adsr~] and [asr~] \, used in [smooth~]. Just set the curve value as a float., f 56;
#X obj 156 148 tgl 19 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 156 172 sig~;
#X text 25 24 The [adsr~] object has attack \, decay \, sustain point and release \, but we can just use the 'decay' phase of it. We'll see more examples and details about this object. For now \, note that it can be controlled by gates (which is the case in the example below) or impulses with a minimum sustain flag., f 52;
#X text 451 73 On the other hand \, the [asr~] object is a simplified version of [adsr~] \, without the decay section and also without the sustain point parameter. By only setting the release phase \, we also implement just a 'decay' envelope. Note that in order for this to work you need to trigger it with an impulse \, which immediately goes to the release phase. We'll see more about this object later as well and for now you can have a good check in the help file of both., f 77;
